# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: unification-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] An anti-unification algorithm should compute for given expressions a complete and minimal generalization set, that is, a set covering all generalizations and containing no redundant members, respectively.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Depending on the framework, a complete and minimal generalization set may have one, finitely many, or possibly infinitely many members, or may not exist at all; it cannot be empty, since a trivial generalization exists in any case.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] For first-order syntactical anti-unification, Gordon Plotkin gave an algorithm that computes a complete and minimal singleton generalization set containing the so-called "least general generalization" (lgg).
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Anti-unification should not be confused with dis-unification.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] The latter means the process of solving systems of inequations, that is of finding values for the variables such that all given inequations are satisfied.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] This task is quite different from finding generalizations.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] For example, if *x* ∈ *V* is a variable symbol, 1 ∈ *C* is a constant symbol, and add ∈ *F*2 is a binary function symbol, then *x* ∈ *T*, 1 ∈ *T*, and (hence) add(*x*,1) ∈ *T* by the first, second, and third term building rule, respectively.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] The latter term is usually written as *x*+1, using Infix notation and the more common operator symbol + for convenience.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] A *substitution* is a mapping $\sigma :V\longrightarrow T$ from variables to terms; the notation $\{x_{1}\mapsto t_{1},\ldots ,x_{k}\mapsto t_{k}\}$ refers to a substitution mapping each variable $x_{i}$ to the term $t_{i}$ , for $i=1,\ldots ,k$ , and every other variable to itself.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Applying that substitution to a term t is written in postfix notation as $t\{x_{1}\mapsto t_{1},\ldots ,x_{k}\mapsto t_{k}\}$ ; it means to (simultaneously) replace every occurrence of each variable $x_{i}$ in the term t by $t_{i}$ .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] The result tσ of applying a substitution σ to a term t is called an *instance* of that term t.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] If a term t has an instance equivalent to a term u , that is, if $t\sigma \equiv u$ for some substitution $\sigma$ , then t is called *more general* than u , and u is called *more special* than, or *subsumed* by, t .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] For example, $x\oplus a$ is more general than $a\oplus b$ if $\oplus$ is commutative, since then $(x\oplus a)\{x\mapsto b\}=b\oplus a\equiv a\oplus b$ .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] If $\equiv$ is literal (syntactic) identity of terms, a term may be both more general and more special than another one only if both terms differ just in their variable names, not in their syntactic structure; such terms are called *variants*, or *renamings* of each other.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] The latter term is hence properly more special than the former one.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] A substitution $\sigma$ is *more special* than, or *subsumed* by, a substitution $\tau$ if $x\sigma$ is more special than $x\tau$ for each variable x .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] For example, $\{x\mapsto f(u),y\mapsto f(f(u))\}$ is more special than $\{x\mapsto z,y\mapsto f(z)\}$ , since $f(u)$ and $f(f(u))$ is more special than z and $f(z)$ , respectively.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] An *anti-unification problem* is a pair $\langle t_{1},t_{2}\rangle$ of terms.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] For a given anti-unification problem, a set S of anti-unifiers is called *complete* if each generalization subsumes some term $t\in S$ ; the set S is called *minimal* if none of its members subsumes another one.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] The framework of first-order syntactical anti-unification is based on T being the set of *first-order terms* (over some given set V of variables, C of constants and $F_{n}$ of n -ary function symbols) and on $\equiv$ being *syntactic equality*.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] In this framework, each anti-unification problem $\langle t_{1},t_{2}\rangle$ has a complete, and obviously minimal, singleton solution set $\{t\}$ .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Its member t is called the *least general generalization (lgg)* of the problem, it has an instance syntactically equal to $t_{1}$ and another one syntactically equal to $t_{2}$ .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Any common generalization of $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$ subsumes t .
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] The lgg is unique up to variants: if $S_{1}$ and $S_{2}$ are both complete and minimal solution sets of the same syntactical anti-unification problem, then $S_{1}=\{s_{1}\}$ and $S_{2}=\{s_{2}\}$ for some terms $s_{1}$ and $s_{2}$ , that are renamings of each other.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Plotkin has given an algorithm to compute the lgg of two given terms.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] It presupposes an injective mapping $\phi :T\times T\longrightarrow V$ , that is, a mapping assigning each pair $s,t$ of terms an own variable $\phi (s,t)$ , such that no two pairs share the same variable.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] For example, $(0*0)\sqcup (4*4)\rightsquigarrow (0\sqcup 4)*(0\sqcup 4)\rightsquigarrow \phi (0,4)*\phi (0,4)\rightsquigarrow x*x$ ; this least general generalization reflects the common property of both inputs of being square numbers.
[src:unification-theory/anti-unification] Plotkin used his algorithm to compute the "relative least general generalization (rlgg)" of two clause sets in first-order logic, which was the basis of the Golem approach to inductive logic programming.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] In computer science, the **occurs check** is a part of algorithms for syntactic unification.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] It causes unification of a variable *V* and a structure *S* to fail if *S* contains *V*.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] In theorem proving, unification without the occurs check can lead to unsound inference.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] For example, the Prolog goal $X=f(X)$ will succeed, binding *X* to a cyclic structure which has no counterpart in the Herbrand universe.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Without occurs check, the literals $p(X,f(X))$ and $p(g(Y),Y)$ are unifiable, producing the refuting empty clause.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Prolog implementations usually omit the occurs check for reasons of efficiency, which can lead to circular data structures and looping.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Implementations, based on Colmerauer's Prolog II, use rational tree unification to avoid looping.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] However it is difficult to keep the complexity time linear in the presence of cyclic terms.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Examples where Colmerauers algorithm becomes quadratic can be readily constructed.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Jaffar’s 1984 work proposed a refinement based on union–find techniques, effectively reducing the worst-case complexity to near-linear time.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Modern systems — including SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, Scryer Prolog, and Ciao Prolog — appear to implement variants of this approach.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] ISO Prolog implementations have the built-in predicate *unify_with_occurs_check/2* for sound unification but are free to use unsound or even looping algorithms when unification is invoked otherwise, provided the algorithm works correctly for all cases that are "not subject to occurs-check" (NSTO).
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] The built-in *acyclic_term/1* serves to check the finiteness of terms.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] Implementations offering sound unification for all unifications are Qu-Prolog and Strawberry Prolog and (optionally, via a runtime flag): XSB, SWI-Prolog, CxProlog, Tau Prolog, Trealla Prolog and Scryer Prolog.
[src:unification-theory/occurs-check] A variety of optimizations can render sound unification feasible for common cases.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog has its roots in first-order logic, a formal logic.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Unlike many other programming languages, Prolog is intended primarily as a declarative programming language: the program is a set of facts and rules, which define relations.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A computation is initiated by running a *query* over the program.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog was one of the first logic programming languages and remains the most popular such language today, with several free and commercial implementations available.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The language has been used for theorem proving, expert systems, term rewriting, type systems, automated planning, and question answering as well as its original intended field of use, natural language processing.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog is a Turing-complete, general-purpose programming language, which is well-suited for intelligent knowledge-processing applications.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The name *Prolog* was chosen by Philippe Roussel, at the suggestion of his wife, as an abbreviation for ****Pro**grammation en **log**ique** (French for *Programming in logic*).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] It was created around 1972 by Alain Colmerauer with Philippe Roussel, from the *Artificial Intelligence Group* of the Faculty of Sciences of Luminy of Aix-Marseille II University of France.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] According to Robert Kowalski, the first Prolog system was developed in 1972 by Colmerauer and Phillipe Roussel.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The first implementation of Prolog was an interpreter written in Fortran by Gerard Battani and Henri Meloni.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Warren took this interpreter to the University of Edinburgh, and there implemented an alternative front-end, which came to define the "***Edinburgh Prolog***" syntax used by most modern implementations.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Warren also implemented the first compiler for Prolog, creating the influential DEC-10 Prolog in collaboration with Fernando Pereira.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Warren later generalised the ideas behind DEC-10 Prolog, to create the Warren Abstract Machine (**WAM**).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] European AI researchers favored Prolog while Americans favored Lisp, reportedly causing many nationalistic debates on the merits of the languages.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Much of the modern development of Prolog came from the impetus of the Fifth Generation Computer Systems project (FGCS), which developed a variant of Prolog named *Kernel Language* for its first operating system.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Pure Prolog was soon extended, however, to include negation as failure, in which negative conditions of the form not(Bi) are shown by trying and failing to solve the corresponding positive conditions Bi.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Subsequent extensions of Prolog by the original team introduced constraint logic programming abilities into the implementations.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Although Prolog is widely used in research and education, Prolog and other logic programming languages have not had a significant impact on the computer industry in general.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Most applications are small by industrial standards, with few exceeding 100,000 lines of code.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Programming in the large is considered to be complex because not all Prolog compilers support modules, and there are compatibility problems between the module systems of the major Prolog compilers.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Software developed in Prolog has been criticised for having a high performance penalty compared to conventional programming languages.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In particular, Prolog's non-deterministic evaluation strategy can be problematic when programming deterministic computations, or when even using "don't care non-determinism" (where a single choice is made instead of backtracking over all possibilities).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Cuts and other language constructs may have to be used to achieve desirable performance, destroying one of Prolog's main attractions, the ability to run programs "backwards and forwards".
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog is not purely declarative: because of constructs like the cut operator, a procedural reading of a Prolog program is needed to understand it.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The order of clauses in a Prolog program is significant, as the execution strategy of the language depends on it.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Other logic programming languages, such as Datalog, are truly declarative but restrict the language.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] As a result, many practical Prolog programs are written to conform to Prolog's depth-first search order, rather than as purely declarative logic programs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Watson uses IBM's DeepQA software and the Apache UIMA (Unstructured Information Management Architecture) framework.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The system was written in various languages, including Java, C++, and Prolog, and runs on the SUSE Linux Enterprise Server 11 operating system using Apache Hadoop framework to provide distributed computing.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog is used for pattern matching over natural language parse trees.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The developers have stated: "We required a language in which we could conveniently express pattern matching rules over the parse trees and other annotations (such as named entity recognition results), and a technology that could execute these rules very efficiently.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] We found that Prolog was the ideal choice for the language due to its simplicity and expressiveness." Prolog is being used in the Low-Code Development Platform GeneXus, which is focused around AI.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Open source graph database TerminusDB is implemented in Prolog.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] TerminusDB is designed for collaboratively building and curating knowledge graphs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In Prolog, program logic is expressed in terms of relations, and a computation is initiated by running a *query* over these relations.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Relations and queries are constructed using Prolog's single data type, the *term*.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Given a query, the Prolog engine attempts to find a resolution refutation of the negated query.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If the negated query can be refuted, i.e., an instantiation for all free variables is found that makes the union of clauses and the singleton set consisting of the negated query false, it follows that the original query, with the found instantiation applied, is a logical consequence of the program.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This makes Prolog (and other logic programming languages) particularly useful for database, symbolic mathematics, and language parsing applications.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Because Prolog allows impure predicates, checking the truth value of certain special predicates may have some deliberate side effect, such as printing a value to the screen.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Because of this, the programmer is permitted to use some amount of conventional imperative programming when the logical paradigm is inconvenient.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] It has a purely logical subset, called "pure Prolog", as well as a number of extralogical features.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog's single data type is the *term*.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Terms are either *atoms*, *numbers*, *variables* or *compound terms*.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog programs describe relations, defined by means of clauses.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Pure Prolog is restricted to Horn clauses.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Two types of Horn clauses are used to define Prolog programs: rules and facts.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] and is read as "Head is true if Body is true".
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A rule's body consists of calls to predicates, which are called the rule's **goals**.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The built-in logical operator `,/2` (meaning an arity 2 operator with name `,`) denotes conjunction of goals, and `;/2` denotes disjunction.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Conjunctions and disjunctions can only appear in the body, not in the head of a rule.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Clauses with empty bodies are called **facts**.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The built-in predicate `true/0` is always true.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Clauses with bodies are called **rules**.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A *predicate* (or *procedure definition*) is a collection of clauses whose heads have the same name and arity.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] We use the notation *name/arity* to refer to predicates.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A *logic program* is a set of predicates.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Predicate `father_child/2` has three clauses, all of which are facts, and predicate `parent_child/2` has two clauses, both are rules.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Due to the relational nature of many built-in predicates, they can typically be used in several directions.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] For example, `length/2` can be used to determine the length of a list (`length(List, L)`, given a list `List`), and to generate a list skeleton of a given length (`length(X, 5)`), and to generate both list skeletons and their lengths together (`length(X, L)`).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Similarly, `append/3` can be used both to append two lists (`append(ListA, ListB, X)` given lists `ListA` and `ListB`), and to split a given list into parts (`append(X, Y, List)`, given a list `List`).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] For this reason, a comparatively small set of library predicates suffices for many Prolog programs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] As a general purpose language, Prolog also provides various built-in predicates to perform routine activities like input/output, using graphics and otherwise communicating with the operating system.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] These predicates are not given a relational meaning and are only useful for the side-effects they exhibit on the system.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] For example, the predicate `write/1` displays a term on the screen.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Iterative algorithms can be implemented by means of recursive predicates.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Consider the `parent_child/2` predicate defined in the family relation program above.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] It expresses that X is an ancestor of Y if X is parent of Y or X is parent of an ancestor of Y.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] It is recursive because it is defined in terms of itself (there is a call to predicate `ancestor/2` in the body of the second clause).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Execution of a Prolog program is initiated by the user's posting of a single goal, called the query.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Logically, the Prolog engine tries to find a resolution refutation of the negated query.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The resolution method used by Prolog is called SLD resolution.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If the negated query can be refuted, it follows that the query, with the appropriate variable bindings in place, is a logical consequence of the program.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In that case, all generated variable bindings are reported to the user, and the query is said to have succeeded.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Operationally, Prolog's execution strategy can be thought of as a generalization of function calls in other languages, one difference being that multiple clause heads can match a given call.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In that case, the system creates a choice-point, unifies the goal with the clause head of the first alternative, and continues with the goals of that first alternative.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If any goal fails in the course of executing the program, all variable bindings that were made since the most recent choice-point was created are undone, and execution continues with the next alternative of that choice-point.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This execution strategy is called chronological backtracking.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The next goal to be proved is the leftmost one of this conjunction, i.e., `parent_child(Z, sally)`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The system creates a choice-point and tries the first alternative, whose body is `father_child(Z, sally)`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This goal can be proved using the fact `father_child(tom, sally)`, so the binding `Z = tom` is generated, and the next goal to be proved is the second part of the above conjunction: `parent_child(tom, erica)`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Again, this can be proved by the corresponding fact.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Since all goals could be proved, the query succeeds.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Since the query contained no variables, no bindings are reported to the user.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] enumerates all valid answers on backtracking.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Notice that with the code as stated above, the query `?- sibling(sally, sally).` also succeeds.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] One would insert additional goals to describe the relevant restrictions, if desired.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The built-in Prolog predicate `\+/1` provides negation as failure, which allows for non-monotonic reasoning.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] is evaluated as follows: Prolog attempts to prove `illegal(X)`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If a proof for that goal can be found, the original goal (i.e., `\+ illegal(X)`) fails.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If no proof can be found, the original goal succeeds.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Therefore, the `\+/1` prefix operator is called the "not provable" operator, since the query `?- \+ Goal.` succeeds if Goal is not provable.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This kind of negation is sound if its argument is "ground" (i.e. contains no variables).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Soundness is lost if the argument contains variables and the proof procedure is complete.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In particular, the query `?- legal(X).` now cannot be used to enumerate all things that are legal.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In Prolog, loading code is referred to as *consulting*.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog can be used interactively by entering queries at the Prolog prompt `?-`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If there is no solution, Prolog writes `no`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If a solution exists then it is printed.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] If there are multiple solutions to the query, then these can be requested by entering a semi-colon `;`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] There are guidelines on good programming practice to improve code efficiency, readability and maintainability.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Here follow some example programs written in Prolog.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This comparison shows the prompt ("?-" vs "| ?-") and resolution status ("true". vs "yes", "false". vs "no") can differ from one Prolog implementation to another.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Any computation can be expressed declaratively as a sequence of state transitions.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A design pattern is a general reusable solution to a commonly occurring problem in software design.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Some design patterns in Prolog are skeletons, techniques, cliches, program schemata, logic description schemata, and higher-order programming.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A higher-order predicate is a predicate that takes one or more other predicates as arguments.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Although support for higher-order programming takes Prolog outside the domain of first-order logic, which does not allow quantification over predicates, ISO Prolog now has some built-in higher-order predicates such as `call/1`, `call/2`, `call/3`, `findall/3`, `setof/3`, and `bagof/3`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] To convert solutions from temporal representation (answer substitutions on backtracking) to spatial representation (terms), Prolog has various all-solutions predicates that collect all answer substitutions of a given query in a list.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This can be used for list comprehension.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This can be used to enumerate perfect numbers, and to check if a number is perfect.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] When `P` is a predicate that for all `X`, `P(X,Y)` unifies `Y` with a single unique value, `maplist(P, Xs, Ys)` is equivalent to applying the map function in functional programming as `Ys = map(Function, Xs)`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Higher-order programming style in Prolog was pioneered in HiLog and λProlog.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] For programming in the large, Prolog provides a module system, which is in the ISO Standard.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] However, while most Prolog systems support structuring the code into modules, virtually no implementation adheres to the modules part of the ISO standard.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Instead, most Prolog systems have decided to support as *de-facto* module standard the Quintus/SICStus module system.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] However, further convenience predicates concerning modules are provided by some implementations only and often have subtle differences in their semantics.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Some systems chose to implement module concepts as source-to-source compilation into base ISO Prolog, as is the case of Logtalk.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] GNU Prolog initially diverted from ISO modules, opting instead for Contextual Logic Programming, in which unit (module) loading and unloading can be made dynamically.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Ciao designed a strict module system that, while being basically compatible with the *de-facto* standard used by other Prolog systems, is amenable to precise static analysis, supports term hiding, and facilitates programming in the large.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] XSB takes a different approach and offers an *atom-based* module system.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The latter two Prolog systems allow controlling the *visibility of terms* in addition to that of predicates.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] There is a special notation called definite clause grammars.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A rule defined via `-->/2` instead of `:-/2` is expanded by the preprocessor (`expand_term/2`, a facility analogous to macros in other languages) according to a few straightforward rewriting rules, resulting in ordinary Prolog clauses.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Most notably, the rewriting equips the predicate with two additional arguments, which can be used to implicitly thread state around, analogous to monads in other languages.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Definite clause grammars are often used to write parsers or list generators, as they also provide a convenient interface to difference lists.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog is a homoiconic language and provides many facilities for reflective programming (reflection).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] where `true` represents an empty conjunction, and `clause(Head, Body)` unifies with clauses in the database of the form `Head :- Body`.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Since Prolog programs are themselves sequences of Prolog terms (`:-/2` is an infix operator) that are easily read and inspected using built-in mechanisms (like `read/1`), it is possible to write customized interpreters that augment Prolog with domain-specific features.
