[src:unification-theory/prolog] Given those, it can be called as `solve(Goal, Certainty)` to execute `Goal` and obtain a measure of certainty about the result.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Pure Prolog is based on a subset of first-order predicate logic, Horn clauses, which is Turing-complete.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This machine performs incrementation by one of a number in unary encoding: It loops over any number of "1" cells and appends an additional "1" at the end.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This illustrates how any computation can be expressed declaratively as a sequence of state transitions, implemented in Prolog as a relation between successive states of interest.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) Prolog technical standard consists of two parts.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] ISO/IEC 13211-1, published in 1995, aims to standardize the existing practices of the many implementations of the core elements of Prolog.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] It has clarified aspects of the language that were previously ambiguous and leads to portable programs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] ISO/IEC 13211-2, published in 2000, adds support for modules to the standard.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The standard is maintained by the ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG17 working group.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] ANSI X3J17 is the US Technical Advisory Group for the standard.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] For efficiency, Prolog code is typically compiled to abstract machine code, often influenced by the register-based Warren Abstract Machine instruction set.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Some implementations employ abstract interpretation to derive type and mode information of predicates at compile time, or compile to real machine code for high performance.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Devising efficient implementation methods for Prolog code is a field of active research in the logic programming community, and various other execution methods are employed in some implementations.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] These include clause binarization and stack-based virtual machines.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog systems typically implement a well-known optimization method called tail call optimization for deterministic predicates exhibiting tail recursion or, more generally, tail calls: A clause's stack frame is discarded before performing a call in a tail position.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Therefore, deterministic tail-recursive predicates are executed with constant stack space, like loops in other languages.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Finding clauses that are unifiable with a term in a query is linear in the number of clauses.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Term indexing uses a data structure that enables sub-linear-time lookups.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Indexing only affects program performance, it does not affect semantics.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Most Prologs only use indexing on the first term, as indexing on all terms is expensive, but techniques based on *field-encoded words* or *superimposed codewords* provide fast indexing across the full query and head.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Some Prolog systems, such as WIN-PROLOG and SWI-Prolog, now implement hashing to help handle large datasets more efficiently.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] This tends to yield very large performance gains when working with large corpora such as WordNet.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Some Prolog systems, (B-Prolog, XSB, SWI-Prolog, YAP, and Ciao), implement a memoization method called *tabling*, which frees the user from manually storing intermediate results.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Tabling can be extended in various directions.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] It can support recursive predicates through **SLG resolution** or linear tabling.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In a multi-threaded Prolog system tabling results could be kept private to a thread or shared among all threads.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] And in incremental tabling, tabling might react to changes.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] During the Fifth Generation Computer Systems project, there were attempts to implement Prolog in hardware with the aim of achieving faster execution with dedicated architectures.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Furthermore, Prolog has a number of properties that may allow speed-up through parallel execution.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A more recent approach has been to compile restricted Prolog programs to a field-programmable gate array.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] However, rapid progress in general-purpose hardware has consistently overtaken more specialised architectures.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In 1982, computers operated at around 10,000 to 100,000 logical inferences per second (LIPS).
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The FGCS planned to produce computers operating at 0.1 to 1 GLIPS.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The Institute for New Generation Computer Technology documents estimated that 1 LIP took about 100 operations on a conventional computer.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The plan was to produce at the end of the project (in 1992) a machine with 1000 processors achieving 1 GLIPS, implying at least 1 MLIPS per processor.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Sega implemented Prolog for use with the Sega AI Computer, released for the Japanese market in 1986.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog was used for reading natural language inputs, in the Japanese language, via a touch pad.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Various implementations have been developed from Prolog to extend logic programming abilities in many directions.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Attempts to introduce and extend Prolog with types began in the 1980s, and continue as of 2008.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Type information is useful not only for type safety but also for reasoning about Prolog programs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] The syntax of Prolog does not specify which arguments of a predicate are inputs and which are outputs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] However, this information is significant and it is recommended that it be included in the comments.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Modes provide valuable information when reasoning about Prolog programs and can also be used to accelerate execution.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Constraint logic programming extends Prolog to include concepts from constraint satisfaction.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A constraint logic program allows constraints in the body of clauses, such as: `A(X,Y) :- X+Y>0.` It is suited to large-scale combinatorial optimisation problems and is thus useful for applications in industrial settings, such as automated time-tabling and production scheduling.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Most Prolog systems ship with at least one constraint solver for finite domains, and often also with solvers for other domains like rational numbers.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Flora-2 is an object-oriented knowledge representation and reasoning system based on F-logic and incorporates HiLog, transaction logic, and defeasible reasoning.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Logtalk is an object-oriented logic programming language that can use most Prolog implementations as a back-end compiler.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] As a multi-paradigm language, it includes support for both prototypes and classes.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Oblog is a small, portable, object-oriented extension to Prolog by Margaret McDougall of EdCAAD, University of Edinburgh.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Objlog was a frame-based language combining objects and Prolog II from CNRS, Marseille, France.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog++ was developed by Logic Programming Associates and first released in 1989 for MS-DOS PCs.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Support for other platforms was added, and a second version was released in 1995.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] A book about Prolog++ by Chris Moss was published by Addison-Wesley in 1994.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Visual Prolog is a multi-paradigm language with interfaces, classes, implementations and object expressions.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog systems that provide a graphics library are SWI-Prolog, Visual Prolog, WIN-PROLOG, and B-Prolog.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog-MPI is an open-source SWI-Prolog extension for distributed computing over the Message Passing Interface.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Also there are various concurrent Prolog programming languages.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Some Prolog implementations, notably Visual Prolog, SWI-Prolog and Ciao, support server-side web programming with support for web protocols, HTML and XML.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] There are also extensions to support semantic web formats such as Resource Description Framework and Web Ontology Language.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] Prolog has also been suggested as a client-side language.
[src:unification-theory/prolog] In addition, Visual Prolog supports JSON-RPC and Websockets.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] In mathematical logic and automated theorem proving, **resolution** is a rule of inference leading to a refutation-complete theorem-proving technique for sentences in propositional logic and first-order logic.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] For propositional logic, systematically applying the resolution rule acts as a decision procedure for formula unsatisfiability, solving the (complement of the) Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] For first-order logic, resolution can be used as the basis for a semi-algorithm for the unsatisfiability problem of first-order logic, providing a more practical method than one following from Gödel's completeness theorem.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The resolution rule can be traced back to Davis and Putnam (1960); however, their algorithm required trying all ground instances of the given formula.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] This source of combinatorial explosion was eliminated in 1965 by John Alan Robinson's syntactical unification algorithm, which allowed one to instantiate the formula during the proof "on demand" just as far as needed to keep refutation completeness.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The clause produced by a resolution rule is sometimes called a **resolvent**.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The **resolution rule** in propositional logic is a single valid inference rule that produces a new clause implied by two clauses containing complementary literals.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] A literal is a propositional variable or the negation of a propositional variable.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Two literals are said to be complements if one is the negation of the other (in the following, $\lnot c$ is taken to be the complement to c ).
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The resulting clause contains all the literals that do not have complements.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The clause produced by the resolution rule is called the *resolvent* of the two input clauses.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] It is the principle of *consensus* applied to clauses rather than terms.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] When the two clauses contain more than one pair of complementary literals, the resolution rule can be applied (independently) for each such pair; however, the result is always a tautology.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Modus ponens can be seen as a special case of resolution (of a one-literal clause and a two-literal clause).
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] When coupled with a complete search algorithm, the resolution rule yields a sound and complete algorithm for deciding the *satisfiability* of a propositional formula, and, by extension, the validity of a sentence under a set of axioms.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] This resolution technique uses proof by contradiction and is based on the fact that any sentence in propositional logic can be transformed into an equivalent sentence in conjunctive normal form.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] One instance of this algorithm is the original Davis–Putnam algorithm that was later refined into the DPLL algorithm that removed the need for explicit representation of the resolvents.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] This description of the resolution technique uses a set *S* as the underlying data-structure to represent resolution derivations.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Lists, Trees and Directed Acyclic Graphs are other possible and common alternatives.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Tree representations are more faithful to the fact that the resolution rule is binary.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Together with a sequent notation for clauses, a tree representation also makes it clear to see how the resolution rule is related to a special case of the cut-rule, restricted to atomic cut-formulas.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] However, tree representations are not as compact as set or list representations, because they explicitly show redundant subderivations of clauses that are used more than once in the derivation of the empty clause.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Graph representations can be as compact in the number of clauses as list representations and they also store structural information regarding which clauses were resolved to derive each resolvent.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] In order for the premise $a\vee b$ to be true, b must be true.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] In order for the premise $\neg a\vee c$ to be true, c must be true.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Therefore, regardless of falsehood or veracity of a , if both premises hold, then the conclusion $b\vee c$ is true.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] where $\phi$ is a most general unifier of $L_{1}$ and ${\overline {L_{2}}}$ , and $\Gamma _{1}$ and $\Gamma _{2}$ have no common variables.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The clauses $P(x),Q(x)$ and $\neg P(b)$ can apply this rule with $[b/x]$ as unifier.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Here x is a variable and b is a constant.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] In first-order logic, resolution condenses the traditional syllogisms of logical inference down to a single rule.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] To recast the reasoning using the resolution technique, first the clauses must be converted to conjunctive normal form (CNF).
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] In this form, all quantification becomes implicit: universal quantifiers on variables (*X*, *Y*, ...) are simply omitted as understood, while existentially-quantified variables are replaced by Skolem functions.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] So the question is, how does the resolution technique derive the last clause from the first two?
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] *X* is an unbound variable, while *a* is a bound value (term).
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Now, unifying *Q*(*X*) in the first clause with ¬*Q*(*Y*) in the second clause means that *X* and *Y* become the same variable anyway.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The resolution rule, as defined by Robinson, also incorporated factoring, which unifies two literals in the same clause, before or during the application of resolution as defined above.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The resulting inference rule is refutation-complete, in that a set of clauses is unsatisfiable if and only if there exists a derivation of the empty clause using only resolution, enhanced by factoring.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Since each clause consists of two literals, so does each possible resolvent.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Therefore, by resolution without factoring, the empty clause can never be obtained.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Generalizations of the above resolution rule have been devised that do not require the originating formulas to be in clausal normal form.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] These techniques are useful mainly in interactive theorem proving where it is important to preserve human readability of intermediate result formulas.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Besides, they avoid combinatorial explosion during transformation to clause-form, and sometimes save resolution steps.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Here $F[p]$ and $G[p]$ denote formulas containing p as a subformula. $F[{\textit {true}}]$ is built by replacing every occurrence of p in $F[p]$ by ${\textit {true}}$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Similarly, $G[{\textit {false}}]$ is built by replacing every occurrence of p in $G[p]$ by ${\textit {false}}$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The resolvent $F[{\textit {true}}]\lor G[{\textit {false}}]$ is intended to be simplified using rules like $q\land {\textit {true}}\implies q$ , etc.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] In order to prevent generating useless trivial resolvents, the rule is applied only when p has at least one "negative" and "positive" occurrence in F and G , respectively.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Murray has shown that this rule is complete if augmented by appropriate logical transformation rules.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] where the exponents of p indicate the polarity of its occurrences.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] While $G[{\textit {true}}]$ and $G[{\textit {false}}]$ are built as before, the formula $F[G[{\textit {true}}],\lnot G[{\textit {false}}]]$ is obtained by replacing each positive occurrence of p in F with $G[{\textit {true}}]$ and each negative occurrence with $G[{\textit {false}}]$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Similar to Murray's approach, appropriate simplifying transformations are to be applied to the resolvent.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Traugott proved his rule to be complete, provided $\land ,\lor ,\rightarrow ,\lnot$ are the only connectives used in formulas.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Traugott's resolvent is stronger than Murray's.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Moreover, it does not introduce new binary junctors, thus avoiding a tendency towards clausal form in repeated resolution.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] However, formulas may grow longer when a small p is replaced multiple times with a larger $G[{\textit {true}}]$ and/or $G[{\textit {false}}]$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] For first-order predicate logic, Murray's rule is generalized to allow distinct, but unifiable, subformulas $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ of F and G , respectively.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] If $\phi$ is the most general unifier of $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ , then the generalized resolvent is $F\phi [{\textit {true}}]\lor G\phi [{\textit {false}}]$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] While the rule remains sound if a more special substitution $\phi$ is used, no such rule applications are needed to achieve completeness.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Traugott's rule is generalized to allow several pairwise distinct subformulas $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{m}$ of F and $p_{m+1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ of G , as long as $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ have a common most general unifier, say $\phi$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The generalized resolvent is obtained after applying $\phi$ to the parent formulas, thus making the propositional version applicable.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Traugott's completeness proof relies on the assumption that this fully general rule is used; it is not clear whether his rule would remain complete if restricted to $p_{1}=\cdots =p_{m}$ and $p_{m+1}=\cdots =p_{n}$ .
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] Paramodulation is a related technique for reasoning on sets of clauses where the predicate symbol is equality.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] It generates all "equal" versions of clauses, except reflexive identities.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The paramodulation operation takes a positive *from* clause, which must contain an equality literal.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] It then searches an *into* clause with a subterm that unifies with one side of the equality.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The subterm is then replaced by the other side of the equality.
[src:unification-theory/resolution-logic] The general aim of paramodulation is to reduce the system to atoms, reducing the size of the terms when substituting.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In logic and computer science, specifically automated reasoning, **unification** is an algorithmic process of solving equations between symbolic expressions, each of the form *Left-hand side = Right-hand side*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For example, using *x*,*y*,*z* as variables, and taking *f* to be an uninterpreted function, the singleton equation set { *f*(1,*y*) = *f*(*x*,2) } is a syntactic first-order unification problem that has the substitution { *x* ↦ 1, *y* ↦ 2 } as its only solution.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Conventions differ on what values variables may assume and which expressions are considered equivalent.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In first-order syntactic unification, variables range over first-order terms and equivalence is syntactic.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] This version of unification has a unique "best" answer and is used in logic programming and programming language type system implementation, especially in Hindley–Milner based type inference algorithms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In higher-order unification, possibly restricted to **higher-order pattern unification**, terms may include lambda expressions, and equivalence is up to beta-reduction.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] This version is used in proof assistants and higher-order logic programming, for example Isabelle, Twelf, and lambdaProlog.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Finally, in semantic unification or E-unification, equality is subject to background knowledge and variables range over a variety of domains.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] This version is used in SMT solvers, term rewriting algorithms, and cryptographic protocol analysis.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A *unification problem* is a finite set *E*={ *l*1 ≐ *r*1, ..., *l**n* ≐ *r**n* } of equations to solve, where *l**i*, *r**i* are in the set T of *terms* or *expressions*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Depending on which expressions or terms are allowed to occur in an equation set or unification problem, and which expressions are considered equal, several frameworks of unification are distinguished.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If higher-order variables, that is, variables representing functions, are allowed in an expression, the process is called **higher-order unification**, otherwise *first-order unification*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If a solution is required to make both sides of each equation literally equal, the process is called **syntactic** or *free* **unification**, otherwise *semantic* or *equational unification*, or **E-unification**, or *unification modulo theory*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If the right side of each equation is closed (no free variables), the problem is called (pattern) *matching*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The left side (with variables) of each equation is called the *pattern*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] As an example of how the set of terms and theory affects the set of solutions, the syntactic first-order unification problem { *y* = *cons*(2,*y*) } has no solution over the set of finite terms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] However, it has the single solution { *y* ↦ *cons*(2,*cons*(2,*cons*(2,...))) } over the set of infinite tree terms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Similarly, the semantic first-order unification problem { *a*⋅*x* = *x*⋅*a* } has each substitution of the form { *x* ↦ *a*⋅...⋅*a* } as a solution in a semigroup, i.e. if (⋅) is considered associative.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] But the same problem, viewed in an abelian group, where (⋅) is considered also commutative, has any substitution at all as a solution.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] As an example of higher-order unification, the singleton set { *a* = *y*(*x*) } is a syntactic second-order unification problem, since *y* is a function variable.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] One solution is { *x* ↦ *a*, *y* ↦ (identity function) }; another one is { *y* ↦ (constant function mapping each value to *a*), *x* ↦ *(any value)* }.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] *Applying* that substitution to a term t is written in postfix notation as $t\{x_{1}\mapsto t_{1},...,x_{k}\mapsto t_{k}\}$ ; it means to (simultaneously) replace every occurrence of each variable $x_{i}$ in the term t by $t_{i}$ .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The result $t\tau$ of applying a substitution $\tau$ to a term t is called an *instance* of that term t .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For example, $x\oplus a$ is more general than $a\oplus b$ if ⊕ is commutative, since then $(x\oplus a)\{x\mapsto b\}=b\oplus a\equiv a\oplus b$ .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If ≡ is literal (syntactic) identity of terms, a term may be both more general and more special than another one only if both terms differ just in their variable names, not in their syntactic structure; such terms are called *variants*, or *renamings* of each other.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The latter term is therefore properly more special than the former one.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For arbitrary $\equiv$ , a term may be both more general and more special than a structurally different term.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For example, if ⊕ is idempotent, that is, if always $x\oplus x\equiv x$ , then the term $x\oplus y$ is more general than z , and vice versa, although $x\oplus y$ and z are of different structure.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A substitution $\sigma$ is *more special* than, or *subsumed* by, a substitution $\tau$ if $t\sigma$ is subsumed by $t\tau$ for each term t .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] We also say that $\tau$ is more general than $\sigma$ .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] More formally, take a nonempty infinite set V of auxiliary variables such that no equation $l_{i}\doteq r_{i}$ in the unification problem contains variables from V .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Then a substitution $\sigma$ is subsumed by another substitution $\tau$ if there is a substitution $\theta$ such that for all terms $X\notin V$ , $X\sigma \equiv X\tau \theta$ .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For instance $\{x\mapsto a,y\mapsto a\}$ is subsumed by $\tau =\{x\mapsto y\}$ , using $\theta =\{y\mapsto a\}$ , but $\sigma =\{x\mapsto a\}$ is not subsumed by $\tau =\{x\mapsto y\}$ , as $f(x,y)\sigma =f(a,y)$ is not an instance of $f(x,y)\tau =f(y,y)$ .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A substitution σ is a *solution* of the unification problem *E* if *l**i*σ ≡ *r**i*σ for $i=1,...,n$ .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Such a substitution is also called a *unifier* of *E*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For a given unification problem *E*, a set *S* of unifiers is called *complete* if each solution substitution is subsumed by some substitution in *S*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A complete substitution set always exists (e.g. the set of all solutions), but in some frameworks (such as unrestricted higher-order unification) the problem of determining whether any solution exists (i.e., whether the complete substitution set is nonempty) is undecidable.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The set *S* is called *minimal* if none of its members subsumes another one.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Depending on the framework, a complete and minimal substitution set may have zero, one, finitely many, or infinitely many members, or may not exist at all due to an infinite chain of redundant members.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Thus, in general, unification algorithms compute a finite approximation of the complete set, which may or may not be minimal, although most algorithms avoid redundant unifiers when possible.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For first-order syntactical unification, Martelli and Montanari gave an algorithm that reports unsolvability or computes a single unifier that by itself forms a complete and minimal substitution set, called the **most general unifier**.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Jacques Herbrand discussed the basic concepts of unification and sketched an algorithm in 1930.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] But most authors attribute the first unification algorithm to John Alan Robinson (cf. box).
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Robinson's algorithm had worst-case exponential behavior in both time and space.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Numerous authors have proposed more efficient unification algorithms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The following algorithm is commonly presented and originates from Martelli & Montanari (1982).
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A set of this form can be read as a substitution.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If there is no solution the algorithm terminates with ⊥; other authors use "Ω", or "*fail*" in that case.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The operation of substituting all occurrences of variable *x* in problem *G* with term *t* is denoted *G* {*x* ↦ *t*}.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For simplicity, constant symbols are regarded as function symbols having zero arguments.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] An attempt to unify a variable *x* with a term containing *x* as a strict subterm *x* ≐ *f*(..., *x*, ...) would lead to an infinite term as solution for *x*, since *x* would occur as a subterm of itself.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In the set of (finite) first-order terms as defined above, the equation *x* ≐ *f*(..., *x*, ...) has no solution; hence the *eliminate* rule may only be applied if *x* ∉ *vars*(*t*).
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Since that additional check, called *occurs check*, slows down the algorithm, it is omitted e.g. in most Prolog systems.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] From a theoretical point of view, omitting the check amounts to solving equations over infinite trees, see #Unification of infinite terms below.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] When rule *eliminate* is applied, *n**var* decreases, since *x* is eliminated from *G* and kept only in { *x* ≐ *t* }.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Applying any other rule can never increase *n**var* again.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] When rule *decompose*, *conflict*, or *swap* is applied, *n**lhs* decreases, since at least the left hand side's outermost *f* disappears.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Applying any of the remaining rules *delete* or *check* can't increase *n**lhs*, but decreases *n**eqn*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Hence, any rule application decreases the triple $\langle n_{var},n_{lhs},n_{eqn}\rangle$ with respect to the lexicographical order, which is possible only a finite number of times.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Conor McBride observes that "by expressing the structure which unification exploits" in a dependently typed language such as Epigram, Robinson's unification algorithm can be made recursive on the number of variables, in which case a separate termination proof becomes unnecessary.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In the Prolog syntactical convention a symbol starting with an upper case letter is a variable name; a symbol that starts with a lowercase letter is a function symbol; the comma is used as the logical *and* operator.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For mathematical notation, *x,y,z* are used as variables, *f,g* as function symbols, and *a,b* as constants.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The most general unifier of a syntactic first-order unification problem of size n may have a size of 2*n*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In order to avoid exponential time complexity caused by such blow-up, advanced unification algorithms work on directed acyclic graphs (dags) rather than trees.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The concept of unification is one of the main ideas behind logic programming.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Specifically, unification is a basic building block of resolution, a rule of inference for determining formula satisfiability.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In Prolog, the equality symbol `=` implies first-order syntactic unification.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] It represents the mechanism of binding the contents of variables and can be viewed as a kind of one-time assignment.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Two constants can be unified only if they are identical.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Similarly, a term can be unified with another term if the top function symbols and arities of the terms are identical and if the parameters can be unified simultaneously.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] So for example `1+2 = 3` is not satisfiable because they are syntactically different.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The use of integer arithmetic constraints `#=` introduces a form of E-unification for which these operations are interpreted and evaluated.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Type inference algorithms are typically based on unification, particularly Hindley-Milner type inference which is used by the functional languages Haskell and ML.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For example, when attempting to infer the type of the Haskell expression `True : ['x']`, the compiler will use the type `a -> [a] -> [a]` of the list construction function `(:)`, the type `Bool` of the first argument `True`, and the type `[Char]` of the second argument `['x']`.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The polymorphic type variable `a` will be unified with `Bool` and the second argument `[a]` will be unified with `[Char]`.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] `a` cannot be both `Bool` and `Char` at the same time, therefore this expression is not correctly typed.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Two type constants unify only if they are the same type.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Two type constructions unify only if they are applications of the same type constructor and all of their component types recursively unify.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Unification has been used in different research areas of computational linguistics.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] After incorporating this algorithm into a clause-based automated theorem prover, he could solve a benchmark problem by translating it into order-sorted logic, thereby boiling it down an order of magnitude, as many unary predicates turned into sorts.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Smolka generalized order-sorted logic to allow for parametric polymorphism.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In his framework, subsort declarations are propagated to complex type expressions.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Schmidt-Schauß generalized order-sorted logic to allow for term declarations.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] As an example, assuming subsort declarations *even* ⊆ *int* and *odd* ⊆ *int*, a term declaration like ∀ *i* : *int*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] (*i* + *i*) : *even* allows to declare a property of integer addition that could not be expressed by ordinary overloading.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For example, if a and b are distinct constants, the equation ⁠ $x*a\doteq y*b$ ⁠ has no solution with respect to purely syntactic unification, where nothing is known about the operator ⁠ * ⁠.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The background knowledge *E* could state the commutativity of ⁠ * ⁠ by the universal equality "⁠ $u*v=v*u$ ⁠ for all *u*, *v*".
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] It is said that *unification is decidable* for a theory, if a unification algorithm has been devised for it that terminates for *any* input problem.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] It is said that *unification is semi-decidable* for a theory, if a unification algorithm has been devised for it that terminates for any *solvable* input problem, but may keep searching forever for solutions of an unsolvable input problem.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If there is a convergent term rewriting system *R* available for *E*, the *one-sided paramodulation* algorithm can be used to enumerate all solutions of given equations.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Starting with *G* being the unification problem to be solved and *S* being the identity substitution, rules are applied nondeterministically until the empty set appears as the actual *G*, in which case the actual *S* is a unifying substitution.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Depending on the order the paramodulation rules are applied, on the choice of the actual equation from *G*, and on the choice of *R*'s rules in *mutate*, different computations paths are possible.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Only some lead to a solution, while others end at a *G* ≠ {} where no further rule is applicable (e.g.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For an example, a term rewrite system *R* is used defining the *append* operator of lists built from *cons* and *nil*; where *cons*(*x*,*y*) is written in infix notation as *x*.*y* for brevity; e.g.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The equational theory *E* corresponding to *R* is the congruence closure of *R*, both viewed as binary relations on terms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The paramodulation algorithm enumerates solutions to equations with respect to that *E* when fed with the example *R*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A successful example computation path for the unification problem { *app*(*x*,*app*(*y*,*x*)) ≐ *a*.*a*.*nil* } is shown below.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] To avoid variable name clashes, rewrite rules are consistently renamed each time before their use by rule *mutate*; *v*2, *v*3, ... are computer-generated variable names for this purpose.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In each line, the chosen equation from *G* is highlighted in red.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Each time the *mutate* rule is applied, the chosen rewrite rule (*1* or *2*) is indicated in parentheses.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] From the last line, the unifying substitution *S* = { *y* ↦ *nil*, *x* ↦ *a*.*nil* } can be obtained.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A second successful computation path, obtainable by choosing "mutate(1), mutate(2), mutate(2), mutate(1)" leads to the substitution *S* = { *y* ↦ *a*.*a*.*nil*, *x* ↦ *nil* }; it is not shown here.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] If *R* is a convergent term rewriting system for *E*, an approach alternative to the previous section consists in successive application of "**narrowing** steps"; this will eventually enumerate all solutions of a given equation.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The situation that *s* can be narrowed to *t* is commonly denoted as *s* ↝ *t*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Intuitively, a sequence of narrowing steps *t*1 ↝ *t*2 ↝ ... ↝ *t**n* can be thought of as a sequence of rewrite steps *t*1 → *t*2 → ... → *t**n*, but with the initial term *t*1 being further and further instantiated, as necessary to make each of the used rules applicable.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The last term, *v*2.*v*2.*nil* can be syntactically unified with the original right hand side term *a*.*a*.*nil*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The *narrowing lemma* ensures that whenever an instance of a term *s* can be rewritten to a term *t* by a convergent term rewriting system, then *s* and *t* can be narrowed and rewritten to a term *s*′ and *t*′, respectively, such that *t*′ is an instance of *s*′.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Formally: whenever *sσ* →∗ *t* holds for some substitution σ, then there exist terms *s*′, *t*′ such that *s* ↝∗ *s*′ and *t* →∗ *t*′ and *s*′ *τ* = *t*′ for some substitution τ.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Many applications require one to consider the unification of typed lambda-terms instead of first-order terms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Such unification is often called *higher-order unification*.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Higher-order unification is undecidable, and such unification problems do not have most general unifiers.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A well studied branch of higher-order unification is the problem of unifying simply typed lambda terms modulo the equality determined by αβη conversions.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Gérard Huet gave a semi-decidable (pre-)unification algorithm that allows a systematic search of the space of unifiers (generalizing the unification algorithm of Martelli-Montanari with rules for terms containing higher-order variables) that seems to work sufficiently well in practice.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Huet and Gilles Dowek have written articles surveying this topic.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Several subsets of higher-order unification are well-behaved, in that they are decidable and have a most-general unifier for solvable problems.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] One such subset is the previously described first-order terms.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] **Higher-order pattern unification**, due to Dale Miller, is another such subset.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] A superset of pattern unification called functions-as-constructors unification is also well-behaved.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The Zipperposition theorem prover has an algorithm integrating these well-behaved subsets into a full higher-order unification algorithm.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] In computational linguistics, one of the most influential theories of elliptical construction is that ellipses are represented by free variables whose values are then determined using Higher-Order Unification.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] For instance, the semantic representation of "Jon likes Mary and Peter does too" is like(*j*, *m*) ∧ R(*p*) and the value of R (the semantic representation of the ellipsis) is determined by the equation like(*j*, *m*) = R(*j*) .
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] The process of solving such equations is called Higher-Order Unification.
[src:unification-theory/robinson-s-unification-algorithm] Wayne Snyder gave a generalization of both higher-order unification and E-unification, i.e. an algorithm to unify lambda-terms modulo an equational theory.
